Sums of Squares in Factorial Models
If each cell (treatment combination) has \(r\) observations, the sums of squares for a main effect or interaction follow a specific pattern: we take (1) the cell means averaged over subscript indices, (2) keep certain signs and expansions, and (3) sum of squares. One can write the sum of squares for an interaction, say \(ABD\), using bracketed averages:
\[
\text{SS}(ABD)
=
r \sum_{i,j,l}
\Big[
\bar{y}_{ij\cdot l\cdot} \;-\; \bar{y}_{ij\cdot\cdot\cdot}
\;-\; \bar{y}_{i\cdot\cdot l\cdot\cdot}
\;-\; \bar{y}_{\cdot j\cdot l\cdot\cdot}
\;+\; \bar{y}_{i\cdot\cdot\cdot\cdot\cdot}
\;+\; \bar{y}_{\cdot j\cdot\cdot\cdot\cdot}
\;+\; \bar{y}_{\cdot\cdot\cdot l\cdot\cdot}
\;-\; \bar{y}_{\cdot\cdot\cdot\cdot\cdot\cdot}
\Big]^2
\]
where \(\bar{y}_{ij.l\cdot}\) is the average over all observations with factor \(A\) at level \(i\), \(B\) at level \(j\), \(D\) at level \(l\), and â€œ\(\cdot\)â€ means averaging over all other subscripts (like factor \(C\) and replicate index \(t\)). Each bracketed difference is then squared and summed over all relevant combinations \(i, j, l\).
For a main effect or any other interaction, the same principle applies: we expand the parentheses with the correct pattern of plus and minus signs, average out the indices that do not appear, square the bracket, and multiply by \(r\) (or by some factor depending on the number of levels omitted).

Degrees of Freedom (Welchâ€“Satterthwaite Formula)
We do not pool variances; each groupâ€™s variance is separately estimated. So the approximate degrees of freedom is given by:
\[
\text{df}
\;\approx\;
\frac{\left(\sum_{i} \frac{c_i^2\,s_i^2}{r_i}\right)^2}
{\sum_{i} \frac{\left(\frac{c_i^2\,s_i^2}{r_i}\right)^2}{r_i-1}},
\]
sometimes called the Satterthwaite or Welchâ€“Satterthwaite formula.

Confidence Intervals
Therefore, an approximate \((1 - \alpha)100\%\) confidence interval for \(\sum_i c_i \tau_i\) becomes:
\[
\sum_i c_i \,\bar{Y}_{i\cdot}
\;\pm\;
t_{\text{df},\,\alpha/2}
\;\sqrt{\sum_i \frac{c_i^2 \, s_i^2}{r_i}},
\]
where \(t_{\text{df},\,\alpha/2}\) is the usual \(t\)-quantile with \(\text{df}\) degrees of freedom from above.

Advanced Features
Customization:

Create reusable functions for subsetting:


filter_cars &lt;- function(data, mpg_threshold, cyl_threshold) {
    data |&gt;
        dplyr::filter(mpg &gt; mpg_threshold, cyl == cyl_threshold)
}

filter_cars(mtcars, 20, 6)






Integration:

Combine tidyr for reshaping with subsetting:


library(tidyr)
mtcars |&gt;
    pivot_longer(cols = everything()) |&gt;
    dplyr::filter(value &gt; 20)

